Predicting Fire Area Damage¶

For this assignment, we will be using linear regresion to forecase fire area damage. We will leverage the Forest Fires Data Set to solve this problem. Additional information regarding this work can be found Cortez and Morais, 2007.

Attribute information:

For more information, read [Cortez and Morais, 2007].

  1. X - x-axis spatial coordinate within the Montesinho park map: 1 to 9
  2. Y - y-axis spatial coordinate within the Montesinho park map: 2 to 9
  3. month - month of the year: "jan" to "dec"
  4. day - day of the week: "mon" to "sun"
  5. FFMC - FFMC index from the FWI system: 18.7 to 96.20
  6. DMC - DMC index from the FWI system: 1.1 to 291.3
  7. DC - DC index from the FWI system: 7.9 to 860.6
  8. ISI - ISI index from the FWI system: 0.0 to 56.10
  9. temp - temperature in Celsius degrees: 2.2 to 33.30
  10. RH - relative humidity in %: 15.0 to 100
  11. wind - wind speed in km/h: 0.40 to 9.40
  12. rain - outside rain in mm/m2 : 0.0 to 6.4
  13. area - the burned area of the forest (in ha): 0.00 to 1090.84 (this output variable is very skewed towards 0.0, thus it may make sense to model with the logarithm transform).

Question 4.1: Develop a simple linear regression model, relating area with rain and wind only. Calculate the predict values based on test data.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# start with the original data
forestfires = pd.read_csv('forestfires.csv')
forestfires['logarea'] = np.log1p(forestfires['area'])

# Split the data into training and testing sets
X = forestfires[['rain', 'wind']]


y = forestfires['logarea']
C = forestfires[['rain', 'wind', 'logarea']]
print(C.cov()) # wanted to see the covariance matrix and which X is more correlated with Y
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=53)

# Create an instance of the LinearRegression model
model = LinearRegression()

# Fit the model to the training data
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict the target variable using the testing data
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

X['day'] = X['day'].map({'mon': 1, 'tue': 2, 'wed': 3, 'thu': 4, 'fri': 5, 'sat': 6, 'sun': 7})

Below I decided to try encoding month differently based on some comments I read in StackExchange about encoding times that are cyclical in nature. The thought being that since Jan and December are similar in weather, they should also have similar values. So I decided to encode the hottest months of the year as 6 and then subtract one from those as we go toward Jan/December.

'jan': 1, 'feb': 1, 'mar': 2, 'apr': 3, 'may': 4, 'jun': 5, 'jul': 6, 'aug': 5, 'sep': 4, 'oct': 3, 'nov': 2, 'dec': 1

The result of this experiment is below. Accuracy didn't appear to improve.

I also tried 2 different experiments:

  1. The first experiment was to just do one-hot encoding of Day/Month data. (this is the one left uncommented as it performed best)
  2. Second I did my less naive mapping of months to numeric values as described above. MSE was worse in this case.
  3. Finally I tried dropping month/day data completely. This also did not perform as well as one-hot encoding them

import numpy as np
forestfires = pd.read_csv('forestfires.csv')
forestfires['area'] = np.log1p(forestfires['area'])

# 1. perform one-hot encoding on the categorical data of month and day
forestfires = pd.get_dummies(forestfires, columns=['month', 'day'])

# 2. Tried mapping month and day to "non-naive" numerical values

# 3. drop the month and day columns completely

X = forestfires.drop('area', axis=1)
